  "market_context": "Educational PDF diagrams comparing how a Market Structure Shift (MSS) and a Change in State of Delivery (CISD) signal bearish-to-bullish or bullish-to-bearish transitions, illustrating the timing difference between the two signals on identical price action.",
  "key_observation": "CISD triggers when price closes below the opening price of a series of up-close candles at an important level, while MSS requires displacement and closure below the prior swing low. CISD typically fires earlier than MSS on the same setup.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Define MSS as a trend change confirmed by displacement and closure beyond a swing high or swing low after a liquidity sweep.",
    "Step 2: Define CISD as a close and displacement below the opening price of an up-close candle (or series) into an important level, validating an order block.",
    "Step 3: Compare both signals on the same diagram, showing CISD line drawn at the up-close candle opens and MSS line drawn at the swing low.",
    "Step 4: Highlight that in the comparison schematic CISD prints above the MSS level, meaning the bearish CISD signal occurs before the swing low is broken.",
    "Step 5: Note that the inverse bullish example shows the same relationship — CISD triggers at the down-close candle opens before price displaces above the swing high to confirm MSS."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "CISD provides an earlier confirmation of directional change than MSS because it focuses on closure through the opposing candle series rather than waiting for displacement beyond a swing point. Use CISD for earlier entries, MSS for stricter structural confirmation.",
